 economic development advisors; women fighting for change as anti-war, anti-nuclear, or Indigenous rights activists; and women engaged in traditional diplomacy. This wide-ranging collection reveals the vital contribution of women to the search for global order that has been a hallmark of Canada’s international history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomen diplomatszCanada. 0aWomen in developmentzCanada. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzCanada. 7aHISTORY / Women .2bisacsh1 aBarker, Stacey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCampbell-Miller, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell-Miller, Jill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClark, Joe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColbourn, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Sharon Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrossen, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonaghy, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonaghy, Greg, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFillion, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirouard, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall, Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarti, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKenzie, Francine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLean, Lorna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoy, Patricia E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWebster, David, e